text:
If you are thinking of doing more of this as a series, I might have a few suggestions that could help make it more streamlined since it seems like you had more you wanted to do than what was shown.  If you want to try to fit it within a certain time, maybe switching to a points system could help.  That way you can set how many questions per section before someone is eliminated and where to put commercial breaks in.  Just an example if 6 is the number of contestants : First round 10 questions (at 100 pt for correct answers and maybe a small break after the 5th question mark to assess who is in the lead or in danger of being eliminated), 1 contestant is eliminated, maybe a commercial break, 8 questions (at 200pt for correct answers and maybe a small break after the 4th question mark to assess who is in the lead or in danger of being eliminated), 1 contestant is eliminated, maybe a commercial break, 6 questions (at 300~400pt for correct answers), double elimination leaving 2 for a head-to-head with final 5 questions.  Maybe have questions that have multiple answers to them in this section so the contestants can get possibly more points each round to possibly get a lead.  500~1,000pt for possible correct answers.  1 winner at the end of it all.  Possible reward for winner or batsu for the losers.  Both can work as well.  You can adjust the number of point value or number of questions to however you want to be longer or shorter than what I've suggested.   I hope this is helpful for you.

Most of the modifiers can be the same.  The only one that would be changed is strike swap.  Since contestants will be eliminated at set intervals instead of calculating whose x is switched or removed, that should be changed to something else.  I have some suggestions and you could add more modifiers if you want.  Suggestion 1: Modifier doubles the points for correct answers of that round for that one question.  Suggestion 2: You get partial points from others guessing correctly if you can't get it right.  Maybe a half of the points of all the correct answers in that question round.  Suggestion 3: Getting a correct answer gives negative points for those who don't get it correct.  Same as the points you'd get correct for that question round but on the negative scale.  Suggestion 4:  Taking a comprehension test to get an extra 250~500 pts.  Maybe smaller for the earlier rounds but bigger for the later rounds.  Suggestion 5: change the subject of the question to something else.  This one might be hard since this means having a stack of questions beforehand.  My earlier suggestion above would amount to 29 questions total (lower if you want the stream shorter) + 6 possible chances for a subject change.   If the amount of subject categories is 5 with 6 questions each to fill the question quota each can possibly answer, then you will need 6 backup questions for each subject for the change.  That means you'd have to have about double the questions of the amount of questions you expect to be answered at minimum for one stream +6 just in case.  More subjects would increase that amount.  More work but you can save those questions for the next game if you plan to have more episodes after and all you have to do is just fill in the subjects missing questions that have already been answered so it's less work for the later episodes in the long run.    I think this will help you greatly if you plan to do future Big Brain Game episodes run more smoothly.    You could also a co-host to bounce off of if you are unsure if the answers the contestant say are correct or not or just generally for banter instead of relying on you alone.   One more suggestion I'd say that you can do is have less trick question questions because people catch on to it quickly if there is too many.  Hope you read this to help you make a better and much efficient Big Brain Games in the future.

Apparently there was a lot of debate about where the Amazon river actually begins, because a lot of different creeks, streams, and smaller rivers all flow into the larger river that is the Amazon, so determining where the "Amazon" river begins was a source of debate. It was only in about 2013 that we actually discovered which of these smaller waterways was the "actual source" of the Amazon river; a small creek flowing in the Andes called Apacheta Creek. By determining that this was the real source of the Amazon, we realized that the Amazon was actually about 350 miles longer than previously recorded, just barely edging it out over the Nile.

Basically, if any of them were drawing on school knowledge from pre-2013, then they couldn't have known. Certainly I didn't. I was convinced Gura was wrong or using improper measurements until I actually looked it up for myself.

text:
Concerning the rules, the "strike swap" mechanic needs more consideration it seems like. It never came up, but imagine this. A person with one strike (Member A) is targeted for a swap by another person (Member B). If A gets the question wrong and B gets it right, this would take A from 1 strike to kicked out of the game. That seems super unfair and unfun. Or what about if A had two strikes and then got the question right, but so did B? Then A would lose the game on a question they got right.

My suggestions for what to do about this:
-Delete strike swap and replace it with strike removal. A one time chance to simply remove your own strike, without giving it to anyone else.
-Delete strike swap and replace with "bonus removal". Getting the question right lets you delete someone else's powerup that they haven't used up till now. If this seems OP, maybe if you use bonus removal and get the question wrong, you lose one of your own remaining bonuses. Under this rule, you aren't allowed to use bonus removal if you don't have a bonus to lose.
-Gura's suggestion to where strike swap can only add a first or second strike, but it can never be the third one. This is still iffy though, if a person with one strike gets a swap AND misses an answer, they can still go out on a turn where otherwise this wouldn't happen, which would likely feel really bad to be on the losing end of.

Heres a few suggestions for the strike system:

- When a player is given a strike from another player they are no longer targetable by future strike swaps. You can call it an anti-bullying policy

- When a players guesses a certain amount of questions they get a "scholarship" lifeline where they can use to block debuffs from other players 1 time

The calendar question was math, if you don't know or remember which months have 30 days.

All you have to do is remember there are 365 days in a non-leap year and know that Feb is 28 days in a non-leap year. 

There are 12 months in a year. 

365 / 12 is 30 with 5 remainder. That means you need at least 5 months with 31 days to make up for the 5 remainder. But wait, there's one month with 2 days less than the average. That means you need 2 more months with 31 days to make up for the deficit. 

That means you have 7 months with 31 days. With February being 28 days, that's 8 months that aren't 30 days. That leaves 4.

Just have to use a bit of reasoning. MATH

text:
imo it's pretty hard to come up with questions whose answers are not debateable. It might take domain knowledge to understand how/where exactly the answer was derived and how to word the question unambiguously. (e.g. the three states of matter could've been tweaked as "What are the three most common states of matter?")

I instead support having several possible correct answers, especially if there's a good argument for one. (e.g. the question on what makes blood red - oxygen is a valid answer too, as is red blood cell, or light. The redness is due to several factors interacting with each other. Maybe for this question, it's better to specify "What molecule makes blood red?" - although oxygen is a molecule too.) Possibly consult chat for it, because chat (who consists of people from all around the world who are knowledgeable in all sorts of niche areas) really does know everything. Could be as simple as letting chat vote whether a particular answer should be accepted or not.
